description: Ethiopia's northern Tigray regional state on Thursday, March 26, announced a region-wide state of emergency as a means of combating the coronavirus pandemic for 15 days.

Ethiopia's northern Tigray regional state on Thursday, March 26, announced a region-wide state of emergency as a means of combating the coronavirus pandemic for 15 days, extended to a duration of 3 months. UPDATE: Extension of the state of emergency to an overall duration of 3 months alongside relaxation of other measures.
Ethiopia's state-owned airline "Ethiopian Airlines" suspends flight operations to 30 countries from March 20.

description: Ethiopia deploys the National Defense Forces to halt the movement of people along all borders, with the exception of incoming essential goods to the country.

Ethiopia deploys the National Defense Forces to halt the movement of people along all borders, with the exception of incoming essential goods to the country. UPDATE: Extension of the closure of all land borders under the state of emergency for five months.

On June 4, Ethiopia is launching the construction of a truck terminal at its borders to Djibouti that provides testing and screening for drivers. The terminals are expected to accommodate 200 trucks at a time and is expected to start in a month.

description: Ethiopia begins screening of all passengers at the Addis Ababa Bole International Airport to curb the import of coronavirus.
As of April 9, Ethiopia's Tigray regional state is obliging local and international travellers entering the state to report to the nearest health office.

On August 14, Ethiopia officially launched the Covid-19 ComBAT campaign which promotes nationwide community mobilisation with testing, screening, surveillance, and public awareness through active public participation.
On September 3, the Ethiopian Public Health Institute launched a SMS based Covid-19 test result notification system that notifies individuals via text message about their results within 3 hours.
As of February 8th, Ethiopia is conducting laboratory testing at the Ethiopian Public Health Institute (EPHI) influenza reference laboratory.
Ethiopia has upgraded a national 8335 toll-free helpline to a digital call centre as of March 15.

The Prime Minister of Ethiopia, with Jack Ma, Founder of the Jack Ma Foundation, and the Alibaba Foundation have jointly launched a relief initiative to support African countries with diagnostics. The donation includes 1.1 million testing kits, 6 million masks and 60,000 protective suits to be distributed throughout Africa. - accounting for 20,000 testing kits, 100,000 medical masks and 1,000 protective suits and face shields per country.

description: As announced from May 3, Ethiopia is starting an operational research initiative seeking to establish a national COVID-19 research task force, led by the Ethiopian Public Health Institute. The initiative seeks to support pandemic preparedness and response activities and involved public and private institutes.

From May 11, the Africa CDC regional agency recruited 20 volunteer public health professionals to support efforts of COVID-19 preparedness and response in Ethiopia throughout its regions and city administration.
On May 18, the Ethiopian Ministry of Health launched a new mobile phone training platform to train frontline health workers and their supervisors on the coronavirus pandemic.
On May 21, Ethiopia increased its number of testing kits through a donation by the Chinese-based Tencent Foundation.

description: On May 26, Ethiopia received a donation of 8.5 tons of medical supplies by the State of Qatar, increasing its stock by 470,000 surgical masks, 70,000 N95 face masks, 60,000 gloves, 57,000 coveralls, 45,000 FF masks, 40,000 FF" masks, 35,000 surgical gowns, 30,000 goggles, and 12,500 face shields.
On June 6, Ethiopia received unspecified medical equipment of the worth of 40 million birr by the Ethiopian Diaspora Trust Fund to fight the COVID-19 pandemic.
Ethiopia's Ministry of Health dispatched 34 youth volunteers to assist health workers in the response to COVID-19 from June 9.
On June 18 2020, Ethiopia donated 15 tons of unspecified COVID-19 medical supplies to the country of Somalia.

description: As of February 8th, Ethiopia is conducting health testing of suspected cases, contacts, quarantined passengers and of randomly collected samples from severe pneumonia cases in selected referral hospitals in Addis Ababa and from the community.

As of February 8th, Ethiopia is conducting health testing of suspected cases, contacts, quarantined passengers and of randomly collected samples from severe pneumonia cases in selected referral hospitals in Addis Ababa and from the community. UPDATE: As of April 1, 2020, Ethiopia has expanded laboratory testing to the National ANimal Health Diagnostic and Investigation Center (NAHDIC) and the Armauer Hansen Research Institute (AHRI).
The Ethiopian region of Tigray deployed 23,000 professionals to screen 1.5 million households in a door-to-door screening activity to detect early symptoms of the virus, announced on April 23.

Ethiopia announced the start of nation-wide testing in all regional states, Addis Ababa, and Dire Dawa city,  for antibodies to COVID-19 to check infection rates and curb the spread of the virus until July 14.

In a ceremony held on August 7, Ethiopia launched a month-long nationwide COVID-19 testing campaign. The campaign aims to test 200,000 people for the virus within two weeks and conducting a door-to-door survey of 17 million citizens.

On August 14, Ethiopia officially launched the Covid-19 ComBAT campaign which promotes nationwide community mobilisation through, testing, screening, surveillance, and public awareness through active public participation.

On June 2, the Ethiopian Public Health institute published detailed hygiene protocol for the process of burials during the COVID-19 pandemic in order to reduce contamination, which are implied to have been in place since March 2020. The measure lasted until June 19, when restrictions were eased.
On June 2, the Ethiopian Public Health Institute released guidelines for water, sanitation, hygiene and waste management for the prevention of COVID-19, which had been in place since April 2020.
On June 2, the Ethiopian Public Health Institute published a protocol for the cleaning and disinfection of areas contacted by COVID-19-suspected or confirmed patients.
Ethiopia is starting to disinfect tourist attraction sites to prepare for a post-COVID period from June 9.
enforcer: National Government,Other (Please specify in the text box)

description: From June 19, Ethiopia is allowing for the burial arrangements of all deaths at home or health facilities to be held by the family at their preferred burial ground once the sample collection is completed, while respecting precautions and restrictions of mass gatherings. The policy is implied to last until the end of the State of Emergency in September 2020.
On June 26, Ethiopia's Hygiene & Behaviour Coalition (HBCC) partners launched a project to run a mass media campaign and to install hygiene facilities at critical locations across Ethiopia.
enforcer: Ministry/Department of Health,Other (Please specify in the text box)

description: On July 23, the Addis Ababa administration introduced a new COVID-19 prevention project for a duration of 6 months under the name "Our Health is in Our Hands" that aims to protect more than 1.2 million people in the capital from the pandemic. The project will distribute sanitation and hygienic supplies to the residents based on family sizes and aims to undertake awareness creation activities among the community on ways of combating the pandemic.

Ethiopia designates special buses to take public servants to work from March 16 for two weeks. UPDATE: Ethiopia designates special buses to take public servants to work from March 16 for two weeks.

Ethiopia expands correction facilities and utilises other holding spaces to avoid overcrowding, while new prisoners will be tested, visits will be suspended and prisoners with minor offences and near released date will be released from imprisonment as of March 20.

description: Ethiopia is announcing actions to be taken against individuals and businesses that are exploiting the health situation and profiting from the above market sell of consumer goods, from March 20. UPDATE: Passengers who cannot afford to be quarantined in designated hotels qill be transferred to Addis Ababa Science and Technology University (ASTU) for a 15 days mandatory quarantine.

compliance: Mandatory with Legal Penalties (Jail Time),Mandatory with Fines

description: From June 19, Ethiopia is demanding individuals suspected of COVID-19 or who tested positive with mild or no symptoms to self-isolate at home, if they have the resources and the support. If they do not meet the self-isolation criteria, they will  be isolated in non-clinical facilities.
compliance: Mandatory with Legal Penalties (Jail Time),Mandatory with Fines

description: From June 19, Ethiopia is enforcing a seven-day mandatory quarantine in government facilities for travellers with no certificate of negative testing on COVID-19, followed by a seven-day self-quarantine at home. compliance: Mandatory with Legal Penalties (Jail Time),Mandatory with Fines

description: Ethiopia in encouraging religious institutions and places of worship to stop gatherings and undertake worship through other means in order to limit and halt the spread of COVID-19 from March 20. description: Ethiopia in encouraging religious institutions and places of worship to stop gatherings and undertake worship through other means in order to limit and halt the spread of COVID-19 from March 20. description: On June 10, Ethiopia postponed the fourth national housing and population census due to the COVID-19 pandemic. The census is postponed to taking place within two years after confirmation by relevant bodies that the pandemic will no longer cause damages to public health.
type_sub_cat: Postponement of an annually recurring event

description: From June 19, Ethiopia is allowing burial arrangements of all deaths at home or health facilities to be held by the family at a preferred burial ground, with attendees of no more than 50 people. The policy is exempt from the restriction on mass gatherings of up to 4 people, which remains in place.
type_sub_cat: Postponement of an annually recurring event

description: On August 1st, the Ethiopian House of Federation (HoF) urged the Tigray regional state to immediately stop its move to hold an election, deemed unconstitutional. After the National Electoral Board of Ethiopia (NEBE) had postponed the 6th national election due to COVID-19, to be held on August 29, the HoF emphasised Tigray's move to be therefore unconstitutional.
type_sub_cat: Postponement of an annually recurring event
